+# Resident Soong: incremental analysis for fast local rebuilds
+
+Status: experimental, opt-in via `SOONG_PERSISTENT_REUSE_GRAPH=true`. Off by
+default; the default build path is unchanged.
+
+This document explains where time goes in an AOSP incremental build, what the
+resident-Soong work changes, why each change is correct, and what remains to
+reach a sub-second warm rebuild. It is written so a reviewer can follow the code
+changes in `build/blueprint` and `build/soong` without prior context.
+
+## 1. Background: how a build runs
+
+An AOSP build has two distinct layers:
+
+```
+  Android.bp files                      build.<config>.ninja            artifacts
+  ───────────────►  soong_build (analysis)  ─────────►  executor (ninja/n2/siso)  ─────────►
+                    parse → resolve → mutate            loads the manifest,
+                    → generate → write ninja            runs the dirty actions
+```
+
+1. **Analysis** (`soong_build`, a Go program): parses every `Android.bp`, resolves
+   dependencies, runs *mutators* (which create per-variant modules and transform
+   properties), calls each module's `GenerateBuildActions`, and writes a single
+   Ninja manifest (`build.<config>.ninja`).
+2. **Execution** (the *executor*): `ninja`, `n2`, or `siso` reads that manifest,
+   builds its in-memory graph, and runs the actions whose inputs changed. soong_ui
+   picks the executor via `SOONG_NINJA` (see `ui/build/config.go`); they all read
+   the same manifest (`ui/build/ninja.go`).
+
+Both layers run as **one-shot processes** today: every `m` re-parses all the
+`Android.bp` files *and* re-loads the whole manifest, even for a one-line edit.
+
+## 2. Where the time goes (measured)
+
+Tree: `aosp_cf_x86_64_phone-trunk_staging`, soong-only, 157 GB RAM machine.
+
+A one-line edit to a leaf `Android.bp`, then `m nothing`:
+
+| phase | cold | notes |
+|---|---:|---|
+| `soong_ui` bootstrap | 5–10 s | env setup, microfactory, nsjail |
+| `parse_bp` | 5 s | parse all 14,130 `Android.bp` |
+| **`resolve_deps` (mutators)** | **34.5 s** | whole-tree dep graph + variant creation |
+| `generateModuleBuildActions` | 22 s | every module's `GenerateBuildActions` |
+| singletons | 15 s | aggregate across all modules |
+| **write `build.ninja`** | **21 s** | 553 MB manifest |
+| executor: load `build.ninja` | ~10 s | parse 553 MB → ~14 GB in-memory graph |
+| the one real compile | ~0.3 s | the only "work" |
+
+Totals ~116 s of overhead to rebuild one file. The on-disk incremental cache
+(`--incremental-build-actions`) does **not** help here (measured 110 s, +RAM): it
+only skips `generateModuleBuildActions`, while `resolve_deps` + write + executor
+load are untouched and it adds a ~9 GB pogreb cache read/write.
+
+The two structural facts that follow:
+
+- The analysis phases are **O(whole tree)** and run every build regardless of how
+  little changed.
+- The executor **re-loads the entire manifest** every build.
+
+## 3. The idea: keep the work resident, redo only the delta
+
+A one-line edit changes one module. Nothing else's analysis output changes. So:
+
+1. Keep the **resolved + mutated module graph in memory** across builds (skip
+   `parse_bp` + `resolve_deps`).
+2. Re-generate build actions for **only the changed modules** (+ any dependents
+   whose inputs changed); keep every clean module's actions as-is.
+3. Skip rewriting the manifest when nothing changed; otherwise patch only the
+   changed parts.
+4. Keep the **executor graph resident** too, so it doesn't re-load 553 MB.
+
+Memory is not the constraint (the graph is ~14 GB; the machine has 157 GB). The
+constraint is that the processes are one-shot.
+
+## 4. What this change implements (the analysis half)
+
+### 4.1 Resident server (`build/soong/cmd/soong_build/persistent.go`)
+
+`soong_build` gains a server mode. When `SOONG_PERSISTENT=true` (or
+`SOONG_PERSISTENT_REUSE_GRAPH=true`), `ui/build/soong.go` sets
+`SOONG_PERSISTENT_SOCK` on the soong_build invocation. soong_build then runs as a
+thin **client** that forwards the build over a unix socket to a long-lived
+**server**.
+
+Critical detail: soong_ui runs the build inside **nsjail** (a PID namespace, see
+`ui/build/sandbox_linux.go`). A server spawned from *inside* nsjail dies when that
+namespace is torn down at build end. So the server must run in the **host
+namespace** — soong_ui runs nsjail as a child, so the host side is outside it. The
+per-build client (inside nsjail) connects to the host server over the socket,
+which is reachable because soong_ui bind-mounts `out/` into the sandbox at the
+same path. A binary-stamp check retires a stale server after `soong_build` is
+rebuilt.
+
+Each request runs on a fresh request-scoped `FlagSet` so no flag state leaks
+between builds.
+
+### 4.2 Graph residency (`build/blueprint/context.go`, `bootstrap/command.go`)
+
+The first build does a full `RunBlueprint` and the server keeps the resolved
+`Context`. Subsequent builds call `bootstrap.RegenerateBuildActions`, which skips
+`list_modules` + `parse_bp` + `ResolveDependencies` and re-enters at
+`PrepareBuildActions`.
+
+`Context.DependenciesReady()` guards this (the graph must be resolved first).
+
+### 4.3 Targeted regeneration (the dirty set)
+
+Re-running *all* modules' `GenerateBuildActions` on a resident graph is both slow
+and **incorrect**: some modules have generate-time global side effects (singletons
+with one-variant guards; `soong_filesystem_creator` *creates* modules during
+generate), so re-running them trips "already generated" / "more than one" guards.
+
+Instead, `Context.MarkModulesDirty(changedNames)` marks the changed modules **plus
+their transitive reverse-dependency closure** as dirty and resets only those.
+`generateModuleBuildActions` then **skips clean modules** (they keep their
+existing `actionDefs`), and `singletonsNeedRegen` skips singletons when nothing is
+dirty. Clean modules are never re-run, so the global-side-effect modules are never
+re-run unless they actually changed.
+
+`Context.preserveLiveGlobals` keeps the global ninja rules/variables/pools from the
+previous generate so clean modules' globals remain emitted.
+
+### 4.4 Re-running generate correctly (single-use state)
+
+Soong's modules are **single-use** for `GenerateBuildActions`. Making them
+re-runnable required handling several pieces of generate-time state. Each fix is
+small and local:
+
+| state | problem | fix |
+|---|---|---|
+| properties slice | grows during generate → re-clone length mismatch | snapshot pristine pre-generate properties in `cloneModules` (`pristineProperties`), restore in `resetModuleBuildActions` |
+| `FreeModuleAfterGenerateBuildActions` | nils `logicModule` mid-pass → dependents visit a nil dep | keep modules live across regenerations |
+| providers | blanket reset wiped **mutator-set** providers (not just generate-set) | snapshot post-mutator providers (`pristineProviders`), restore them; generate re-sets only its own indices |
+| `SingletonModule` one-variant guard | factory returns a shared instance, guard stays set | `SingletonModuleBase.ResetBuildActionsState()` hook, called from the reset |
+| `EventHandler` | events accumulate across builds → `CompletedEvents` duplicate-id panic | `EventHandler.Reset()` per build |
+| background metrics | `collectMetrics` sends on a channel with no reader → deadlock | call `StartBackgroundMetrics` per warm build |
+
+### 4.5 Skip the manifest write when nothing changed
+
+`Context.NinjaUnchanged()` reports a targeted regenerate with zero dirty modules.
+`RegenerateBuildActions` then skips the 553 MB `WriteBuildFile` entirely (soong
+still touches the output so the executor sees it as newer than the edited
+`Android.bp`). When modules *are* dirty, the manifest is rewritten (patching only
+the changed statements is a planned follow-up).
+
+## 5. Correctness
+
+The invariant is: **the resident build's `build.ninja` is byte-identical to a
+clean full build for the same sources.** Validated with `cmp` on a comment-only
+edit (0 dirty): identical across repeated warm builds.
+
+The default build path (flag off) is completely unchanged → zero regression.
+
+Limitation (honest): re-applying an *edited property* through the mutators is not
+yet implemented (`detectChangedModules` is a stub). The mechanism is validated for
+graph-neutral edits; arbitrary edits need the change-detection in §7. Soong's
+mutators do not declare which properties they read, so the change-detection must
+be **conservative**: fall back to a full `RunBlueprint` for any edit it cannot
+prove is graph-neutral (a full build is always correct).
+
+## 6. Results
+
+A one-line `Android.bp` edit, `SOONG_PERSISTENT_REUSE_GRAPH=true`:
+
+| | cold | warm |
+|---|---:|---:|
+| total `m nothing` | ~117 s | ~11 s |
+| soong analysis | ~95 s | **~ms** (resolve_deps + generate + singletons skipped) |
+
+The warm residual (~11 s) is now entirely the **executor re-loading the 553 MB
+manifest (~10 s) + soong_ui bootstrap (~1.5 s)** — the analysis bottleneck is
+gone. Those are addressed by the executor half (§7).
+
+## 7. Roadmap to sub-second warm
+
+1. **Change-detection** (analysis): re-parse only the edited `Android.bp` (via
+   mtime/inotify), diff each module's properties against the resident graph, and
+   feed `MarkModulesDirty`; fall back to a full `RunBlueprint` for structural
+   edits (added/removed module, dependency change, mutator-consumed property).
+   Prune the reverse-dep closure with provider hashes so unaffected dependents
+   stay clean.
+2. **Incremental manifest write**: when N modules are dirty, rewrite only their
+   ninja statements instead of the whole 553 MB.
+3. **Resident executor** (the ~10 s): keep the executor's parsed graph in memory
+   across builds. This is executor-specific and goes behind the existing
+   `ninjaCommand` switch (`ui/build/ninja.go`):
+   - **ninja**: a resident command-index daemon (prototype: ~11 MB resident,
+     21 µs no-op, replays only the affected command) or a ninja-server patch.
+   - **siso**: lean on siso's native persistent/incremental model.
+4. **Daemon entry point**: `m` is one-shot, so it can never be sub-second on its
+   own. Sub-second *warm* requires a resident daemon holding both the soong graph
+   and the executor graph, with the user action as a thin trigger (optionally
+   inotify-driven). The two resident halves above compose into it.
+
+### Phase 2 (separate, larger): CI integration
+
+A persistent build server on CI (e.g. TreeHugger) that keeps the resident graph
+warm across changes and patches+builds only the per-change delta, reusing the same
+resident-analysis + resident-executor architecture. Out of scope here.
+
