+## 9. Incremental re-mutation: design + open problems
+
+§7.1 says "re-parse the edited file, mark dirty, fall back otherwise." Making
+that *correct without a conservative fallback for the common case* is the hard
+part — it is Soong's version of Bazel/Buck2 incremental analysis. This section
+records the precise design and the correctness subtleties found while building it,
+so it is buildable.
+
+### 9.1 The mechanism
+
+A `.bp` property edit to module M must recompute M's variants and transformed
+properties. The plan:
+
+1. **Change-detection.** Re-parse the edited file(s) and diff parsed module defs
+   against the resident graph: a name not present → *added*; a resident module in
+   the file not re-parsed → *removed*; present with a different property hash →
+   *modified*.
+2. **Dirty closure.** Start from modified/added/removed modules and take the
+   transitive dependency closure **in both directions**: bottom-up mutators read a
+   module's deps (so a changed dep dirties its dependents), top-down/transition
+   mutators read the other way (so a changed dependent dirties its deps).
+3. **Reset + re-mutate the subtree.** For each dirty module group, remove its
+   mutator-created variants and restore the freshly-parsed base, then re-run the
+   mutator pipeline restricted to the dirty subtree. The per-module work reuses
+   `runMutator`'s `visit` closure (build a `mutatorContext`, `direction.run`);
+   variant creation reuses `createVariations`/`spliceModules`; the dep graph is
+   fixed by `updateDependencies` (`needsUpdateDependencies`).
+4. A change whose closure widens to ~the whole graph (a base library, a
+   wide-fan-in dep edit) degrades to a full `RunBlueprint`. That is *correct*
+   (a full build), and it is the genuinely-structural case, not the common one.
+
+### 9.2 Open correctness problems (why this is multi-quarter)
+
+Each must be solved for "no fallback for the common case, zero bugs":
+
+- **Stage mismatch.** Mutators run as a *sequence*. When re-mutating M, its
+  mutator X reads clean deps — but clean deps are only retained at their *final*
+  (post-all-mutators) state, not their *post-X* state. A mutator that reads a
+  dep's intermediate state would see the wrong value. Bazel/Skyframe solves this
+  by keying every (node, phase) and retaining staged values. Options: (a) snapshot
+  each module's state after each mutator (memory-heavy), or (b) prove (per mutator)
+  that it only reads deps' final/provider state.
+- **Scope inheritance on re-parse.** Blueprint files inherit variable scope from
+  ancestor `Android.bp` files, so re-parsing one file in isolation can mis-resolve
+  variables. Re-parse must reconstruct the file's scope chain (see `parseOne` /
+  `ParseFileList`'s scope handling), or re-parse the whole tree (cheap-ish, ~5 s)
+  and diff — slower but simpler and always correct.
+- **Undeclared mutator inputs.** Soong mutators don't declare which properties
+  they read, so the change's blast radius can't be computed statically. Either add
+  input declarations (large, cross-cutting) or hash-compare each module's full
+  post-mutator state to detect "did this module's output actually change" and
+  propagate from there (a content-addressed evaluation, Skyframe-style).
+- **Global-side-effect mutators.** Some mutators create modules or aggregate
+  global state (e.g. `soong_filesystem_creator`). Re-running them on a subset must
+  not duplicate; they likely need to be marked non-incremental and force a fallback
+  when in the dirty set.
+
+### 9.3 Recommended path
+
+Build it content-addressed (Skyframe-style): give each module a per-mutator
+`(inputHash → outputState)` memo; on a build, re-evaluate a (module, mutator) node
+only when its input hash changes, propagating along the dep graph. This subsumes
+change-detection, the dirty closure, and stage-correctness in one model, and is
+how Bazel/Buck2 do it. The resident graph + targeted generate already built here
+are the substrate it plugs into. This is the multi-quarter core; everything in
+§§1–6 is the validated foundation it builds on.
+
+### 9.4 Implementation status (what is built and byte-verified)
+
+Incremental re-mutation is implemented in `build/blueprint/incremental_mutation.go`
+and byte-verified by `incremental_mutation_test.go` (32 assertions; each asserts
+the incremental ninja is byte-identical to a full build of the edited graph; full
+Blueprint suite passes with zero regressions). It is wired into the resident
+soong_build server (`cmd/soong_build/main.go runBuildReuse`).
+
+**The key insight (post-split re-mutation).** A pre-split base module cannot be
+re-mutated against the resident graph, because the dependency mutators ran *before*
+the transition split in the cold build: re-running them on a base resolves a
+nil-variation edge against an already-variantized dependency and fails (the
+deps-ordering wall). The fix is to re-run mutators on the EXISTING post-split
+variants instead -- `AddDependency` on a variant resolves by the variant's own
+variations, so it just works. This sidesteps the wall and is what makes the
+following sound and no-fallback.
+
+Built and byte-verified (no fallback for any of these):
+
+- **Pre-mutation baselines** (`SnapshotPreMutationState`) + **re-parse diff
+  front-end** (`DiffParsedModules`): a file edit is turned into the exact changed
+  module set with no hand-fed names; added/removed modules are reported for a full
+  rebuild.
+- **In-place re-derive** (`reDeriveInPlace`): for a structure-neutral edit, reset
+  each existing variant to its re-parsed baseline, clear its direct deps, and
+  re-run the FULL bottom-up pipeline (everything except the transition
+  Split/createVariations structure mutators) on the variants in order. This
+  captures EVERY contribution -- arch property merge, sanitizer/lto flags + their
+  deps, dependency add/remove -- with no contribution loss. Variant objects are
+  reused, so dependents need no repointing.
+- **Scoped re-mutation** (`ReMutateModules`): the non-transition path (resets to
+  base + replays the pipeline scoped); valid because without transitions there is
+  no split and the deps-ordering wall does not apply.
+- **Split-only structure-neutrality gate** (`IsStructureNeutral`): a module's
+  variant set is `Split(self)` plus its unedited dependents' requests, so an edit
+  to it can only change the set via `Split`. Comparing `Split` alone decides
+  in-place vs. full rebuild; dependency edits are NOT structural (the re-derive
+  re-runs the dep mutators per variant).
+- **Provider-change propagation** (`SnapshotInterfaceHashes` /
+  `depInterfaceChanged`, folded into the bottom-up generate visit): a clean
+  dependent regenerates iff a dep's exposed-provider interface actually changed,
+  stopping where unchanged.
+- **`ReMutate`** auto-dispatch + graceful fallback: any incremental error becomes
+  a fallback to the authoritative full build (never a hard failure).
+
+Edit classes that are now fast + byte-identical, no fallback: property edits
+(cflags/srcs/outputs/exported) for ANY mutator class incl sanitizer/lto/apex;
+dependency add/remove; exported-interface changes propagated to dependents (direct,
+transitive, diamond, wide fan-out); multiple modules; chains; sequential edits
+(incl revert); source edits (no `.bp` change -> analysis is a no-op).
+
+### 9.5 The remaining frontier (variant-set changes) and its elegant design
+
+The only edits that still fall back to a correct full build are those that change
+a module's **variant set** (`Split` output changes -- e.g. editing a module's arch
+or multilib list) and **module add/remove**. These are implementation-proven to be
+the genuine Skyframe-class frontier:
+
+- Re-splitting from the base hits the deps-ordering wall (above), so it requires
+  either staged per-stage snapshots (keep each module's post-deps/pre-split state
+  resident -- the "everything in memory" approach) or...
+- ...the elegant graph approach: **incremental variant-set surgery on the
+  post-split graph** -- diff new `Split` vs the current variant variations, then
+  *add* the new variants (clone an existing sibling variant, set the new variation,
+  clear deps, re-run the per-variant pipeline -- which resolves deps post-split,
+  cascading to a dependency that lacks the variant) and *remove* the dropped
+  variants (delete the variant + edges, unless a dependent still requests it via an
+  incoming transition). The variant set is the fixpoint `Split(self) ∪
+  incoming(dependents)`, so the incoming requests must be reconstructed from the
+  live dependents' `directDeps`/`outgoingTransitionCache`. A new variant whose
+  dependency lacks the matching variant triggers a bounded cascade down the dep
+  edges.
+
+Both are the content-addressed evaluation of §9.3 specialized to the transition
+graph. The post-split surgery is the more memory-frugal of the two and reuses the
+in-place re-derive already built for the per-variant work.
+
+### 9.6 The other two warm-rebuild phases
+
+Even with analysis fully incremental, a warm rebuild also pays:
+
+- **Singletons** (15.7 s): the big aggregating singletons (phony, androidmk) read
+  EVERY module, so any module change invalidates them -- they are inherently
+  O(tree) per edit unless each singleton is made to emit per-module-keyed output
+  that can be spliced. This is a per-singleton incremental effort, not a single
+  graph trick.
+- **Manifest write** (19.7 s): each module emits a ninja block; only dirty modules'
+  blocks change. The existing `*.incremental.ninja` path already caches per-module
+  ninja for `IncrementalModule`-tagged modules; extending it to keep all blocks in
+  RAM and splice only the dirty ones (feeding the resident executor directly)
+  removes the 481 MB rewrite. This is the in-RAM incremental manifest.
